{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a91b2c04",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Global Power Plant Database\n",
    "\n",
    "## Project Description.\n",
    "\n",
    "The Global Power Plant Database is a comprehensive, open source database of power plants around the world. It centralizes power plant data to make it easier to navigate, compare and draw insights for one’s own analysis. The database covers approximately 35,000 power plants from 167 countries and includes thermal plants (e.g. coal, gas, oil, nuclear, biomass, waste, geothermal) and renewables (e.g. hydro, wind, solar). Each power plant is geolocated and entries contain information on plant capacity, generation, ownership, and fuel type. It will be continuously updated as data becomes available.\n",
    "Key attributes of the database\n",
    "\n",
    "### The database includes the following indicators:\n",
    "•\t\n",
    "•\t`country` (text): 3 character country code corresponding to the ISO 3166-1 alpha-3 specification [5]\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`country_long` (text): longer form of the country designation\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`name` (text): name or title of the power plant, generally in Romanized form\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`gppd_idnr` (text): 10 or 12 character identifier for the power plant\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`capacity_mw` (number): electrical generating capacity in megawatts\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`latitude` (number): geolocation in decimal degrees; WGS84 (EPSG:4326)\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`longitude` (number): geolocation in decimal degrees; WGS84 (EPSG:4326)\n",
    "•\t`primary_fuel` (text): energy source used in primary electricity generation or export\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`other_fuel1` (text): energy source used in electricity generation or export\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`other_fuel2` (text): energy source used in electricity generation or export\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`other_fuel3` (text): energy source used in electricity generation or export\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t `commissioning_year` (number): year of plant operation, weighted by unit-capacity when data is available\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`owner` (text): majority shareholder of the power plant, generally in Romanized form\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`source` (text): entity reporting the data; could be an organization, report, or document, generally in Romanized form\n",
    "•\t`url` (text): web document corresponding to the `source` field\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`geolocation_source` (text): attribution for geolocation information\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`wepp_id` (text): a reference to a unique plant identifier in the widely-used PLATTS-WEPP database.\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`year_of_capacity_data` (number): year the capacity information was reported\n",
    "•\t`generation_gwh_2013` (number): electricity generation in gigawatt-hours reported for the year 2013\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`generation_gwh_2014` (number): electricity generation in gigawatt-hours reported for the year 2014\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`generation_gwh_2015` (number): electricity generation in gigawatt-hours reported for the year 2015\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`generation_gwh_2016` (number): electricity generation in gigawatt-hours reported for the year 2016\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`generation_gwh_2017` (number): electricity generation in gigawatt-hours reported for the year 2017\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`generation_gwh_2018` (number): electricity generation in gigawatt-hours reported for the year 2018\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`generation_gwh_2019` (number): electricity generation in gigawatt-hours reported for the year 2019\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`generation_data_source` (text): attribution for the reported generation information\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`estimated_generation_gwh_2013` (number): estimated electricity generation in gigawatt-hours for the year 2013\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`estimated_generation_gwh_2014` (number): estimated electricity generation in gigawatt-hours for the year 2014 \n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`estimated_generation_gwh_2015` (number): estimated electricity generation in gigawatt-hours for the year 2015 \n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`estimated_generation_gwh_2016` (number): estimated electricity generation in gigawatt-hours for the year 2016 \n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`estimated_generation_gwh_2017` (number): estimated electricity generation in gigawatt-hours for the year 2017\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`estimated_generation_note_2013` (text): label of the model/method used to estimate generation for the year 2013\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`estimated_generation_note_2014` (text): label of the model/method used to estimate generation for the year 2014 \n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`estimated_generation_note_2015` (text): label of the model/method used to estimate generation for the year 2015\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`estimated_generation_note_2016` (text): label of the model/method used to estimate generation for the year 2016\n",
    "\n",
    "•\t`estimated_generation_note_2017` (text): label of the model/method used to estimate generation for the year 2017 \n",
    "\n",
    "Fuel Type Aggregation\n",
    "\n",
    "We define the \"Fuel Type\" attribute of our database based on common fuel categories. \n",
    "\n",
    "### Prediction :   Make two prediction  1) Primary Fuel    2) capacity_mw \n",
    "\n",
    "## Dataset Link-\n",
    "•\thttps://github.com/wri/global-power-plant-database/blob/master/source_databases_csv/database_IND.csv\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

    "# Observations from this column \n",
    "\n",
    "### We see that there are a lot of null values in this dataset , lets break it down:-\n",
    "\n",
    "- We see that the columns other_fuel2, other_fuel3,wepp_id,generation_gwh_2013,generation_gwh_2019 ,estimated_generation_gwh all are emplty columns as all the values are null, so we need to remove these columns\n",
    "- we see other fuel1, owner, generation_gwh_2014,generation_gwh_2016,generation_gwh_2017,generation_gwh_2018,generation_data_source,commissioning_year,year_of_capacity_data all have significant amount of Null values and we need to study them and treat them indefinetely\n",
    "\n",
    "- we see that latitude and longitude,geolocation_source has have some NULL as well \n",
    "\n",
    "- the rest dont have any NULL but this data set overall has too many NULL values which we need treat as we cant created the model with it "
   ]

    "## Treating the 'generation_gwh_2014','generation_gwh_2015', 'generation_gwh_2016', 'generation_gwh_2017', 'generation_gwh_2018'"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "af6e26fb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We see that these columns have continuos data and have valuable info which will go into predicting the label and we have a large no of nan values in these columns.\n",
    "\n",
    "We also cannot delete them as the rows in other years have values and we dont want to remove those values and not have the model use that info to predict\n",
    "\n",
    "and we cant replace with 0 as then it would become an outlier , so the only wasy we can treat according to my analysis is replacing the NAN values with the mean of the column , that way it wont affect the skewness and we will also be able to have a better prediction for the label primary fuel as well as capacity mw"
   ]
  },

    "We see that there are some very extreme values in the rows lets analyse them one by one:-\n",
    "\n",
    "    - we see that std of columns capacity_mw,'generation_gwh_2014','generation_gwh_2015', 'generation_gwh_2016', 'generation_gwh_2017', 'generation_gwh_2018'are higher than the mean , which should not be the case, we have high skewness in these coulmns which we need to treat  \n",

  },

    "# We are defining numerical & categorical columns\n",
    "numeric_features = [feature for feature in df.columns if df[feature].dtype != 'O']\n",
    "categorical_features = [feature for feature in df.columns if df[feature].dtype == 'O']\n",
    "\n",
    "# print columns\n",
    "print('We have {} numerical features : {}'.format(len(numeric_features), numeric_features))\n",
    "print('\\nWe have {} categorical features : {}'.format(len(categorical_features), categorical_features))"

   "id": "f58f15e0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We seed to treat the skewness of the data onl for features and non categorical data \n",
    "\n",
    "- we see that capacity is one of the label so we will treat it only when calcualting for primary_fuel \n",
    "\n",
    "- the columns 'generation_gwh_2014','generation_gwh_2015', 'generation_gwh_2016', 'generation_gwh_2017','generation_gwh_2018' all have skewnesss so we will need to treat them accordingly\n",
    "\n",
    "- we see some categorical columns such as source and logitude , bu we cant delete as one is the category columns and the other is a location metric which we need to pinpoint the location"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 100,
   "id": "6c4f0bdf",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#making the skew less than or equal to 0.55 for better prediction and plotting Normal distribution\n",
    "\n",
    "skew=('generation_gwh_2014','generation_gwh_2015', 'generation_gwh_2016', 'generation_gwh_2017','generation_gwh_2018')\n",
    "\n",
    "for col in skew:\n",
    "    if df.skew().loc[col]> 0.55:\n",
    "        df[col] = np.log1p(df[col])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 101,
   "id": "47928d4e",

    "# we are first calculating the skew value and some of the column skew value are far from zero almost 6 so its diificult to make a good model with this.\n",
    "\n",
    "- The best skew value for normally distributes is very close to zero, so we are using “log1p” method to make the skew value near to zero\n",
    "- In the last cell I am again checking the skewness value and there is difference between the first skewness value and second, now the skewness value of each column is near to zero.\n",
    "\n",
    "- Making the skewness value near to zero will help to get better score."

    "# Using SelectKBest Feature Selection Method -1st Target - Capacity_mw\n",
    "\n",
    "Select KBest use f_classif function to find the best features, where f_classif uses Anova Test"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 118,
   "id": "030f9a3a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Again we Divide data into features and label\n",
    "\n",
    "X = df.drop(columns = ['capacity_mw'])\n",
    "y = df['capacity_mw']"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 119,
   "id": "574d3b73",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest, f_classif"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 120,
   "id": "28a9a9c5",
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": true
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "           Feature_name     Score\n",
      "11   geolocation_source  3.663012\n",
      "9          primary_fuel  3.194679\n",
      "6   generation_gwh_2018  3.185584\n",
      "8             gppd_idnr  3.086688\n",
      "5   generation_gwh_2017  3.037998\n",
      "4   generation_gwh_2016  2.841442\n",
      "2   generation_gwh_2014  2.253522\n",
      "3   generation_gwh_2015  2.108368\n",
      "10               source  1.665490\n",
      "1             longitude  1.572093\n",
      "0              latitude  1.333466\n",
      "7                  name  0.870904\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "best_features = SelectKBest(score_func = f_classif, k=12)\n",
    "\n",
    "fit = best_features.fit(X,y)\n",
    "\n",
    "df_scores = pd.DataFrame(fit.scores_)\n",
    "\n",
    "df_columns = pd.DataFrame(X.columns)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "#concatenate dataframes\n",
    "\n",
    "feature_scores = pd.concat([df_columns, df_scores], axis = 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "feature_scores.columns = ['Feature_name', 'Score']   #name output columns\n",
    "\n",
    "print(feature_scores.nlargest(12,'Score'))  #Print Best 4 features"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f4205780",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### We see that thescores for the columns are pretty similar in this case and there are different slabs approx , where some columsn are in 3-4 range and some 2-3 and some 1-2 range and the name columns is showing almost 0 which means its not contributing to the label"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d350b064",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Variance Inflation Factor\n",
    "\n",
    "Checking for Multicollinearity problem to see if one feature is dependent on the other , we need to scale the dat first using MINMAX Scalar"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 121,
   "id": "f01558cf",

   "outputs": [],

    "#Finding variance inflation factor in each scaled column i.e X_scaled.shape[1] (1/(1 -R2))\n",

    "best_features = SelectKBest(score_func = f_classif, k=12)\n",
    "\n",
    "fit = best_features.fit(X2,y2)\n",
    "\n",
    "df_scores = pd.DataFrame(fit.scores_)\n",
    "\n",
    "df_columns = pd.DataFrame(X2.columns)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "#concatenate dataframes\n",
    "\n",
    "feature_scores = pd.concat([df_columns, df_scores], axis = 1)\n",
    "\n",
    "feature_scores.columns = ['Feature_name', 'Score']   #name output columns\n",
    "\n",
    "print(feature_scores.nlargest(12,'Score'))  #Print Best 17 features"

     ]

   ],

    "from sklearn.ensemble import AdaBoostRegressor\n",
    "ada = AdaBoostRegressor()\n",
    "\n",
    "ada.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "ada.score(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "pred_decision =ada.predict(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "adas = r2_score(y_test,pred_decision)\n",
    "print('R2 Score :',adas*100)\n",
    "\n",
    "adascore = cross_val_score(ada,X,y,cv=8)\n",
    "adac =adascore.mean()\n",
    "print('Cross Val Score :',adac*100)\n"

    "## Hyper parameter Tuning"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 176,
   "id": "87bf2eeb",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Fitting 8 folds for each of 250 candidates, totalling 2000 fits\n",
      "{'criterion': 'mse', 'max_features': 4, 'min_samples_leaf': 3, 'n_estimators': 200}\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV\n",
    "from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor\n",
    "\n",
    "#Creating parameters to pass in GridSearchCV\n",
    "\n",
    "parameters = {'criterion':['mse','mae'],\n",
    "             'max_features':['auto','sqrt','log2'],\n",
    "             'max_features': [ 3, 4 ,5, 6, 7],\n",
    "             'min_samples_leaf': [3, 4, 5, 6, 7],\n",
    "             'n_estimators' : [100,200,300,400,500]\n",
    "             }\n",
    "rf=RandomForestRegressor()\n",
    "clf= GridSearchCV(rf,parameters,verbose=2,cv=8,n_jobs=-1)\n",
    "clf.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(clf.best_params_)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 177,
   "id": "13e31aa9",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",

    "rf.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "rf.score(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "pred_decision =rf.predict(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "rfs = r2_score(y_test,pred_decision)\n",
    "print('R2 Score :',rfs*100)\n",
    "\n",
    "rfscore = cross_val_score(rf,X,y,cv=8)\n",
    "rfc =rfscore.mean()\n",
    "print('Cross Val Score :',rfc*100)\n"
   ]

    "X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test = train_test_split(X,y,test_size = 0.25,random_state = 35) \n",
    "\n",
    "# as the best random state we have chosen is 78"
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 190,
   "id": "062c2583",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#Write one function and call as many times to check accuracy_score of different models\n",
    "\n",
    "def metric_score(clf,X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test,train=True):\n",
    "    if train:\n",
    "        y_pred = clf.predict(X_train)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        print(\"\\n===============================Train Result=============================\")\n",
    "        \n",
    "        print(f\"Accuracy score : {accuracy_score(y_train,y_pred) * 100: .2f}%\")\n",
    "        \n",
    "    elif train == False:\n",
    "        pred = clf.predict(X_test)\n",
    "        \n",
    "        print(\"\\n===============================Test Result===============================\")\n",
    "        print(f\"Accuracy Score : {accuracy_score(y_test,pred) * 100: .2f}%\")\n",
    "        \n",
    "        \n",
    "        print ('\\n \\n Test Classification Report \\n', classification_report(y_test, pred, digits = 2)) ##Model Confidence /Accurancy\n",
    "        "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 191,
   "id": "cc7357ac",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

    "\n",
    "dts = accuracy_score(y_test,pred_decision)\n",

    "## Hyper parameter Tuning"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 203,
   "id": "6c45acb4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Fitting 9 folds for each of 100 candidates, totalling 900 fits\n"
     ]
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "{'n_estimators': 200,\n",
       " 'min_samples_split': 4,\n",
       " 'min_samples_leaf': 1,\n",
       " 'max_features': 'sqrt',\n",
       " 'criterion': 'entropy'}"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 203,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV\n",
    "from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier\n",
    "rf= RandomForestClassifier()\n",
    "\n",
    "#Creating parameters to pass in RandomizedSearchCV\n",
    "\n",
    "parameters = {'criterion':['gini','entropy'],\n",
    "             'max_features':['auto','sqrt','log2'],\n",
    "             'min_samples_split': [1, 2, 3, 4 ,5],\n",
    "             'min_samples_leaf': [1, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7],\n",
    "             'n_estimators' : [100,200,300,400,500]\n",
    "             }\n",
    "\n",
    "RCV = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator = rf,param_distributions = parameters, n_iter = 100, cv = 9, verbose=2, random_state=35, n_jobs = -1,scoring='accuracy')\n",
    "RCV.fit(X_train,y_train) #fitting data into the model\n",
    "RCV.best_params_ #printing the best parameters found by the RandomizedSearchCV"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 204,
   "id": "d2c07682",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Accuracy Score : 87.7659574468085\n",
      "Cross Val Score : 85.2059029769873\n",
      "[[ 1  1  0  5  0  0  2  1]\n",

    "\n",

    "\n",
    "rf.fit(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "rf.score(X_train,y_train)\n",
    "pred_decision =rf.predict(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "rfs = accuracy_score(y_test,pred_decision)\n",
    "print('Accuracy Score :',rfs*100)\n",
    "\n",
    "rfscore = cross_val_score(rf,X,y,cv=9)\n",

   ]
